\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1852626\charrsid1852626 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1852626\charrsid1852626 
So could we start by saying where and when were you born?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1852626\charrsid1852626 Ruth:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1852626\charrsid1852626 
I was born in Londonderry, but you might want to call it Derry \endash  that\rquote s already a political statement \endash  in Northern Ireland, on the 31}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\super\langnp2057\insrsid1852626\charrsid1852626 st}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1852626\charrsid1852626 
 December, 1933, at home, because that, of course, was the system then. My parents, at that time, were living in the gro
unds of Magee College, which, at that time, was a college that had been founded the previous century for training Presbyterian Ministers, and my father taught Classics \endash  Latin and Greek \endash 
 there.  And I was the first of five children.  I was the oldest, and then in due course I got three brothers and a sister, all of whom I\rquote m still quite close to, and three of whom still live in Northern Ireland, though they\rquote 
ve travelled the world first, but then decided that was the best place to live.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1852626\charrsid1852626 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1852626\charrsid1852626 And so was you
r father interested in the literature of the Classics?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1852626\charrsid1852626 Ruth:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1852626\charrsid1852626 
Yes, but also very much interested in the application of Classics to the wider world.  I mean, it\rquote s quite interesting - may I go back and tell you a little bit about his ancestry?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1852626\charrsid1852626 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1852626\charrsid1852626 Please 
do!  Please do, yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1852626\charrsid1852626 Ruth:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1852626\charrsid1852626 
Because looking back now, I realise it has had quite an influence on me.  His father, a native Ulsterman, so Finnegan is an unusual name in Ulster \endash  most people would think it was Southern and Catholic \endash  somewhere, some Finnegan
s must have turned coat and come up and got into the ascendance in Northern Ireland!  But anyway, he studied \endash  my grandfather, that is father\rquote s father, John Finnegan \endash  studied at Queen\rquote 
s, in Belfast, and then went across to UCL and studied physics, and then came back and did various things like teaching.  But interestingly \endash  and this is what I look back to particularly \endash 
 became the first Secretary, a senior officer like Registrar, of Queen\rquote s University, just after it became properly open to people from all 
traditions - in other words, Catholics as well as Protestants.  In theory it had been, but 1908-1909 was when it }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1852626\charrsid7368951 really }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1852626\charrsid1852626 did, and my grandfather, John Finnegan, stayed there for 16 years, and that was the period in which there were these huge challenges of 
opening to all sections of the community, and he, it was said, was really the guiding hand that led that.  They were a very obviously open-minded and international family, because I know my father grew up with a German governess, and that also very much i
nfluenced him all his life, because he was a German-speaker \'85 well, up to a point.  And then my father - first of all did Classics at Queen\rquote 
s, and then went across to Cambridge to do a sort of second top-up degree, and I think he wondered about going into the Church and doing theology, but actually didn\rquote t \'85
 but taught for a while in a school, and then went to Magee College.  He was very very much tied up with the Student Christian Union, and the whole story is to do with that, but just going on with the Univ
ersity thing, during his life, my father was instrumental in turning Magee College from a Presbyterian-dominated place into a University College, which meant it had to be an Act of Parliament \endash  this was later, after the War \endash 
 which was then open to all sec
tions of the community, and Catholics, and he had to work very very hard to do that.  So I feel both my grandfather and my father were very much instrumental in opening higher education to all sections of the community, and I can\rquote 
t help connecting that with my own views about the Open University.  So that\rquote s just one strand in my father\rquote s life.  I mean, there were other ones.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1852626\charrsid1852626 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1852626\charrsid1852626 
Other important strands worth mentioning?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1852626\charrsid1852626 Ruth:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1852626\charrsid1852626 
Well, there were two other important strands.  One was his politics, which was also very much influenced by my mother \endash 
 there are more stories about that.  But they were both very concerned, again, to bring Catholic and Protestant together, which was not a bit easy in the North of Ireland there.  I mean, even I growing up in such a 
liberal, open-minded family, grew up subconsciously thinking the world was divided into two things \endash 
 the Catholics who were a bit irrational, and the Protestants who maybe were a bit dogmatic and Puritanical, but, nevertheless, they were kind of rational!  Don\rquote 
t tell me how I could have got that idea, but anyway, they were very concerned to combat that.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid11871832  A}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid6974344 nd they were also very l}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1852626\charrsid1852626 
eft-wing, and one of the things they did in the thirties was to build up, really for the first time in Derry - which was the second
 city of Northern Ireland - a Labour Party which was across Catholic and Protestant.  I remember, even as a small child, the dockers coming into the house, and me thinking they were rather rough but liking them, and they did a great deal \endash 
 my parents \endash  to try to get better conditions for the dockers who had no sort of Health and Safety and proper equipment, they were always getting injured.  So that was very important in my life.  They didn\rquote 
t really succeed, the Catholic/Protestant divisions went on, but they really did quite a bit to build that up \endash  before the War.  Then, of course, things changed in the War.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1852626\charrsid1852626 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1852626\charrsid1852626 
And you were aware of this as a child?
\par 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid16188492 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1852626\charrsid1852626 Ruth:\tab }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1852626\charrsid1852626 I was aware of this as a child, but I was born the last day of 1933, and when the War came, we ac
tually moved away from our house in the College grounds, because the Navy wanted to take it over.  They took it over, and we actually went and lived in Donegal, so we were removed from all that.  So I remember a bit before the War, and then when we came b
ack again after the War, things were all a bit different.  But I do remember both some of the visits of these dockers \endash 
 one, I remember, gave me, a bulldog puppy, which proved to be a most awful gift, because it got into fights with all the other dogs in th
e neighbourhood, and we had to get rid of it!  (LAUGHS)  But I can still remember that!  But I also remember them talking about it, you know, as time went on, and after the War, so I think, again, that had a big influence on me.  But the second thing abou
t my father, aided and abetted by my mother, but she was more practical about it, was that he was a Pacifist, and felt very strongly about that.  There were a number of people in Northern Ireland, I\rquote 
m now discovering, who were like that.  It was partly tied up, I think, with the Student Christian Union.  It was very much a high-principled moral stand.  My mother was always more practical, she didn\rquote 
t quite approve of high principles, but she actually very much supported him.  But then, when the War came, it w
as also tied up with his knowledge and friendship with Germans, and he was very much stigmatised by particularly the Presbyterians and the police, as being a Nazi-lover and so on \endash 
 you can imagine, during the War.  In fact, he and some of his friends - I don\rquote 
t know the details -had been very instrumental in the late thirties, in helping to get Jews out of, particularly Austria, though I think he also tried in Germany, but didn\rquote 
t quite manage it, and so we grew up knowing some of these wonderful Austrian Jew
s who were settled in Derry, partly through the work that he and certain colleagues did.  And he and others were really trying to put pressure on to the British government, in the thirties, to try to do something about the awful oppression.  So it was alw
ays a }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid5582457\charrsid1852626 bit ironic}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1852626\charrsid1852626 
 that he was so stigmatised as being a Nazi-lover.
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid1852626 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1852626\charrsid1852626 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1852626\charrsid1852626 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1852626\charrsid1852626 
Which was their Church, then?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1852626\charrsid1852626 Ruth:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1852626\charrsid1852626 
Presbyterian, very much my father\rquote s, and he\rquote d grown up that, and used to go to First Derry Presbyterian Church, which I always really quite hated, because it was so cold and upright.  My mother always hated that church, and she\rquote 
d grown up more with the Congregationalist Church, but it was in some ways, quite close, but she wasn\rquote 
t quite so devoted to going to church, though she had very strong principles in some ways.  But I was very proud of my father, in many ways. I used to go to school from Donegal, during the War, it used to be very embarrassing,
 because we were all supposed to take in \endash  I don\rquote t know if you had this as well \endash  War Savings to school.  You would take in your pennies and so on for the War Savings, and we weren\rquote 
t allowed, by our parents, to take any, so you really felt, in one way, quite proud, but in another way you just wanted to cower away as being the odd one out.  (LAUGHS)
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1852626\charrsid1852626 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1852626\charrsid1852626 
Yes.  And would you like to say something about your mother?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1852626\charrsid1852626 Ruth:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1852626\charrsid1852626 Sorry?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1852626\charrsid1852626 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1852626\charrsid1852626 
Would you like to say something about your mother?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1852626\charrsid1852626 Ruth:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1852626\charrsid1852626 Yes.  She was 
a really great character.  Great story teller.  Her parents very much were from the West side of Northern Ireland, from the Donegal side \endash 
 the men in it were, but a lot of them went over to Scotland for their wives - or Yorkshire, I think, was my grandmother.  And her earlier forbears had done really quite well in business and were quite well-off, and her grandfather \endash  her father
\rquote s father - and his wife had had many many children, many of whom went off to become missionaries abroad: in India, Madagascar, an
d one had emigrated to Canada, there were a whole lot of them.  The women, of course, stayed behind, and looked after the missionaries\rquote  children!  But my mother\rquote 
s father, who was the second son, was the one who was supposed to stay at home and mind the bus
iness, which was then a flour importing mill, and he was really bad at business, he really wanted to go off and watch birds, or be a missionary, and do all the interesting things, so he went bankrupt. So they were very badly off, and I think my mother, an
d her mother, always really rather resented that the others had managed to fly free, and he\rquote 
d had to stay.  But they were Protestant, but Nationalist, which is slightly unusual mixture, and that, again, very much influenced my mother, who was the youngest of four surviving children \endash  one died in infancy \endash 
 and she always wanted to be the rebel.  She was the youngest.  Very lively, very talkative, very chatty.  She went to Queen\rquote s, Belfast, and did English Literature, which women did, but not all women did, and that\rquote 
s where she met my father.  But all her life rebelled against particularly the Presbyterian view of the wife and mother who stayed at home.  She was a wonderful mother, and absolutely totally devoted herself to her children, in our early years, but 
never really wanted to stay in Derry, she wanted to travel the world. Yet that\rquote s where my father got - she said to him, \'93I\rquote ll go with you to the end of the world.  Anywhere, except Derry\'94
, but it was Derry that she had to settle down in!  But she occupied herself in lots of political work, and helping to organise children\rquote s playgrounds, and just being a personality and a lively talkative, chatty person, around.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1852626\charrsid1852626 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1852626\charrsid1852626 
So how close were you to both your father and your mother?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1852626\charrsid1852626 Ruth:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1852626\charrsid1852626 Well, my father was very
 much the Ulster man, and father\rquote s weren\rquote 
t that close to their children.  He was quite shy, actually, and so we never had a very chatty relationship. But we saw quite a lot of each other because I remember, particularly, during the War, in Donegal, for som
e of the time we were living in a great old house seven miles outside Derry, and he used to cycle in, every day, for his work, and for a lot of the time I used to cycle in as well, to school - to begin with, on the back of a tandem with him, so we had a l
o
t of time chatting there. And he also very much approved of me wanting to go on and do Classics, which was my first degree, which followed on for him, and he taught me a great deal.  And he had lovely Irish - Ulster wit, and twinkle.  But we were never cl
ose - we were, intellectually, and we had great respect for each other, but not kind of chatty chatty, whereas my mother, she was really into everything, and she lived much longer than my father \endash  he died in his early sixties \endash  and I\rquote 
ve always been very close to her.  She had a big influence.  And all of her children, her five children, adored her!  And also slightly laughed at her exaggerated stories with kind of exaggerated laughing, teasing pride.
