\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid12015233 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1852626\charrsid1852626 Ruth:\tab }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1852626\charrsid1852626 Yes, well, that\rquote s quite typically complex \endash 
 as it would always be in Northern Ireland.  The first school I went to, of course, was pre-War, because that was while we were still in Derry. If you come from Northern Ireland, you would know this before I even told you, the Londonderry High School
 which, of course, was Protestant, and was on the Northland Road, which was the Protestant Road. There were also Catholics around that side of the Foyle \endash  the river that divided the city \endash 
 but in our little enclave it was all Presbyterian. And that was ver
y much a traditional grammar-like kind of school, but I began in the kindergarten.  Actually, I can remember my first day, come to think of it, because I remember we we went along, I must have been quite young, and we had to use scissors to cut up somethi
ng and stick it together, and for some reason, they forgot to give me any scissors, and I was too shy to ask for any!  So I just tore the things up, and then I was very much reproached for not }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid5190179 having asked for the scissors!  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1852626\charrsid1852626 But then when the War came, and 
we went off, first of all - no, what had happened was that my parents had always spent their holidays in a particular place in Donegal \endash  Sheephaven, near a place called Portnabla. My mother\rquote s family always had, they\rquote 
d gone from Derry, and at that time, the
re was a railway, and then when they were married, my father used to go there too.  And they had seen this half-built cottage on a very remote strand, and had decided to buy it.  And I think it must have been 1940, we\rquote 
d gone down there for the first time over Easter, for a fortnight \endash  it was still only kind of semi-built \endash 
 we were very lucky, there was water, one tap outside the front door, but mostly we had to carry it from the well. And while we were there - I think my father must have been still working 
at Magee, and we were mostly there, and he was just coming down - the Navy came and said they wanted to take over - this particular house [in Derry] we were in, because it had a very good view down of the docks and the Naval port.  And this was [usually] 
all full of children.  Well, I mean, since we were all away, my father, who was terribly terribly truthful \endash  my mother wouldn\rquote t have done this, perhaps \endash  said, \'93Well, no, no, no children here at the moment\'94
. So they took it over.  So we spent a whole year in this very remote cottage, which my mother just thought was the most wonderful thing, because she\rquote d never been in such close contact with the country and countrymen. She hadn\rquote 
t known which end of a cow really was which, and yet we had to have a cow to get milk from!  When I was there, I was seven, and just learning to read, because I was quite late learning to read, much to my mother\rquote s pleasure \endash  she didn\rquote 
t think children should be doing such silly things as reading when they could be out looking at nature, which is quite right, actually!  But I lea}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid12015233 
rnt to read while I was there.  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1852626\charrsid1852626 
And I went to the little local school, Ballymore School, which was associated with the Ballymore Church of Ireland Church, which was about, I don\rquote 
t know, two miles, three miles walk across the bog, and I used to go with an older girl usually. That was very much the traditional Dame School almost!  Children were slapped if they got things wrong, and I think there were 11 pupils in my class, and then
 there was a tiny little bit - so there were just two teachers.  You would say that there were so many things that were not quite what we would want nowadays, but I always think that that\rquote 
s where I learnt how to learn.  They did lots of mental arithmetic, lots of spelling bees, lot}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid930210 s of \lquote quick quick\rquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1852626\charrsid1852626  things.  We did parsing, and paraphrasing, and things you would never do nowadays.  And we did careful writing \endash  not that my writing ever has been wonderful \endash 
 it should have been after that!  And we learnt little bits of Irish.  Really, it was wonderful.  And then I would do a lot of reading at home, and having just learnt to read, I was immediately plunged into things like }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1852626\charrsid1852626 The Odysseys }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1852626\charrsid1852626  and }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\i\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1852626\charrsid1852626 Cahoulan\rquote s Stories}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1852626\charrsid1852626 , and just left on with them \endash 
 that was wonderful, reading by candlelight!  I know the main teacher was called Miss Park, I think so, I don\rquote t particularly remember them as individuals, but I do just remember thinking, \'93Learning things is just wonderful!\'94
  So I owe so much to that school.  And then we came back.
