\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1852626\charrsid1852626 Ruth:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1852626\charrsid1852626 
Where we were in Donegal? Well, it was on the West Coast of Donegal.  There\rquote s a big bay called Sheephaven Bay, and then lots of little bays, and this was near a place called Portnabla, which was much}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1852626\charrsid930210  the}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1852626\charrsid1852626 
 place that people went, but it was inland - well, not really inland, but along the coast from that, in a remote, unfrequented little bay, little inlet/estuary, where, at that time, there were only a couple o
f houses of the local carpenter and the local postman, both of whom had their own little farming plots, and then one other farm just further out near the headland, sheep farm.  Now, there are quite a number of houses there, but we were very very remote.  
And there\rquote s a place called Cloonm}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13970465 ass, and where we were was the \lquote Back Strand\rquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1852626\charrsid1852626 , it was called \endash  which shows how remote it was \endash  and that was about 42 miles from Derry.  And during that year, just over a year that we were there \endash  1940/41 
\endash  my father was still working at Magee, and he used to cycle down at the weekends, arriving well after us children were asleep, and leaving early during the night on the Sunday night.  He was very tough, because that was quite hard.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1852626\charrsid1852626 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1852626\charrsid1852626 
Quite a distance. And the place that you were in, in Donegal, earlier, was much nearer to Derry?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1852626\charrsid1852626 Ruth:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1852626\charrsid1852626 
No.  That was the first place that we, as a family, were, in Donegal, apart from earlier holidays there, which was equally far from Derry, that was the 
first place we lived there.  But then, in 1941, I think my parents decided that we really needed to be nearer bigger schools, and my father needed to be nearer to his work, so we moved from there and spent about three years in a great old Georgian house, 
actually \endash  falling down, falling down \endash  we rented it.  And that was the one that was seven miles from Derry, where we used to cycle in.  Yes.  Yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1852626\charrsid1852626 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1852626\charrsid1852626 
Yes.  Yes, I understand. Fascinating!
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1852626\charrsid1852626 Ruth:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1852626\charrsid1852626 
But that year in Donegal just changed my mother\rquote s life and outlook.  She said, \'93Nothing has ever been so great\'94
.  And we still have that cottage.  It still is there, the family cottage, now with electricity and proper water and so on, but very much unites the whole family.  It, technically, belongs to my sister 
Clare.  She lives close, and they look after it wonderfully, but anyone in the family is just welcome there.  So it\rquote s a big symbol of the family \endash  that cottage.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1852626\charrsid1852626 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1852626\charrsid1852626 
Good.  And then after that, where did you go to school after that?
\par 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid13970465 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1852626\charrsid1852626 Ruth:\tab }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1852626\charrsid1852626 Then when we c
ame back to Derry again - while we were the seven miles out, I went to the Londonderry High School, back again.  And then we came back to Derry after the War, and I continued to go. It was just like five }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13970465\charrsid1852626 minutes\rquote  walk}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1852626\charrsid1852626 , and the real Grammar School type!  We
 learnt French grammar very properly, lots of geometry, got promoted up to the top class \endash 
 I remember that, that was very frightening, because you had to go up - you were called up to the board, and you had to write up the latest Pythagoras theorem that you\rquote 
d learned - and English and Latin.  And I was, meantime, reading and reading and reading lots of things. I remember reading all the way through Scott\rquote 
s novels, greatly enjoying that!  But then when I was 13, my parents decided I should go away to school. I always think, looking back, they made such financial sacrifices for that, because they really weren\rquote 
t at all well-off.  And they hated, particularly my mother, but both of them, hated to be parted from their children.  But I think their reasoning was th
at they really could see how children grew up in Northern Ireland with the religious prejudices that there were, and they just wanted to give their children something wider than that.  I think they also felt that they would get a better academic education
