 The Mount - quite a well-known independent Quaker School.  There were Quaker connections in the family, because my mother\rquote s oldest sister, Helen, was very much a leading member of the Society of Friends, and though my parents weren\rquote 
t Quakers, my father\rquote s Pacifism had brought him very much into connection with the Quaker circles because, of course, they were very leading Pacifists.  My mother\rquote 
s next sister, Dora, who lived in Liverpool - or near Liverpool, West Kirby - her daughters, twin daughters, who were slightly older than u}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13970465 
s, had gone to a Quaker School.  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1852626\charrsid1852626 So I was sent to The Mount.  I always hated leaving hom
e, I used to be in floods of tears, leaving home!  My poor parents!  And, of course, it was quite a journey as well.  I had to go by train to Belfast, and then the boat, and it always seemed to make me seasick!  We had terrible crossings!  And then by tra
i
n the other side.  There were people I went with. But once I got there, I was actually very happy. And in the narrow academic sense, I was miles ahead of the children there, and the teaching was really, at that time, pretty rotten - you know, teachers who
 couldn\rquote t keep order.  Some were really good, but really, I was shocked by some of the things that went on there!  But the music and the drama were just great, and I wouldn\rquote 
t have missed out on that for anything.  I made some very good friends there.
