\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1852626\charrsid1852626 Ruth:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1852626\charrsid1852626 
Yes.  Yes.  Then there was a companion boys\rquote  school \endash  Bootham \endash 
 where my two younger brothers went to, and that my cousin, son of the same Dora, in Liverpool, went to as well - who was just older than my two brothers. We had a certain amount to do with them, but rather at arms\rquote 
 length, until my last term of school, where our Classics teacher left, and we were sent across to the boys\rquote  school, and that was great for lessons.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1852626\charrsid1852626 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1852626\charrsid1852626 
So what were you specialising in by that stage?
\par 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid12285211 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1852626\charrsid1852626 Ruth:\tab }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1852626\charrsid1852626 Well, to begin with, it was all very general, of course, and we were doing School Cert
ificate, I think, at that time, and I decided, with one very good friend, that we wanted to do Greek.  I was influenced by my father, of course, I suppose!  So we did Greek in one year for School Certificate, which was looking back, I mean, it was quite t
o
ugh, because we read lots of Greek texts straightaway, quite difficult ones.  And so we worked like anything at that, and that was great fun.  And a lot of other things I enjoyed as well.  I loved the maths.  There was a very very good history teacher, sh
e was great.  And we did read some interesting literature as well, even though the liter}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid12285211 ature teacher was a bit funny!  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1852626\charrsid1852626 So having done Greek for School Certificate, for Higher, I went for Classics \endash  again, perhaps influenced by my father.  But also - I mean
 Greek was lovely!  So we did Greek, Latin, Ancient History, with the idea that I would \endash  this was what my parents, I think, had always hoped and destined me for \endash 
 that I would try for Oxford after that. Because though I was a girl, and, therefore girls didn\rquote t quite need the same sort of education in Ulster, as boys, I was the oldest, and therefore, in my father\rquote 
s eyes, like a boy.  And so I did those three things for Higher - like \lquote A\rquote  Level now.  The School was really good.  We still did lots of literature
, and a bit of French. I very very much wanted to go on with maths, and for a while was able to do it, because I really liked it \endash 
 not for an exam.  But after a while, I think I could only, because of time-table clashes, go to two out of three lessons, and when they got on to calculus, I found that two out of three \endash  though I was bright \endash  two out of three just wasn
\rquote t quite enough, so I think, after one year, I stopped doing that, which I really regretted.  But the teachers we had, you said, who influenced m
e?  Well, as I say, the history teacher earlier, [Miss Nicolson] was.  But the teacher we had for Latin, Greek and Ancient History, was a big influence. I mean, this sounds terrible!  In some ways, she was an awful teacher [but] she was so enthusiastic, s
o she was a wonderful teacher.  There were three of us by that time doing it.  The Ancient History, which she didn\rquote 
t really know an awful lot about, what she used to do was to write out long accounts, which she then read aloud to us, and we would write it d
own word for word and learn it.  What do you think of that for history teaching!  But the great thing about it was that she often got it wrong!  And so the three of us aided and abetted each other in running round, finding out, checking up and finding out
 what was right.  Can you actually think of a better preparation, because it really encouraged us to read round, go to the library \endash  it was a good library \endash 
 check up on things, form our own ideas. I think that was just a wonderful preparation for university work!  So}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid12285211  she was just so enthusiastic!  }{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1852626\charrsid1852626 Then she left at the end of - just after we\rquote 
d done Higher, and you probably remember, at that time, if you wanted to try for Oxford or Cambridge, you had to stay on for one extra term. So we went across to the boys\rquote  school, and had a wonderful teacher there \endash  Mr. Burt \endash 
 who, you know, these boys had all learned Greek forever, and they were so good, and they all ended up doing very well - or two of them did, I don\rquote t know what happened to one of the others.  And that was a real challenge to us, because I\rquote 
d always found it was easy to be the best!  But they knew }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid12285211 so much. That was really good.  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1852626\charrsid1852626 Then I got offers at both Oxford and Cambridge, I think - that\rquote s right, because, then, you could take it both.  I think my father was disappointed that I didn\rquote 
t get a Scholarship, whereas I thought it was so brilliant, as a girl, to get in at all, because at that time, it was really easier to get a Scholarship as a man, than it was even to get in as a girl!  But I did have, because I\rquote 
d done well at Higher, I got a State Exhibition as they called it, and the local government, and still it was as big sacrifice for my parents.  It\rquote 
s not just now that people build up debts as a student.  But I just loved doing Classics in the sixth form, and then at university. When I was interviewed at Somerville \endash  which is where I went \endash 
 the person interviewing me said what was I going to do with my two terms in between?  And I said \endash  because this is what my parents had encouraged me to think of doing \endash  \'93Maybe I might go to Germany and learn German\'94
, which is what my mother had done at that stage.  And she said, \'93But what will happen to your Latin and Greek, Miss Finnegan, in the meantime?\'94  Of course, you know, I didn\rquote t really know an awful lot of Lati
n and Greek!  (LAUGHS)  Though I somehow got in!  So actually, what I did was, I stayed in Derry and went to some lectures, and had some tutoring in Classics at Magee College, where my father was teaching \endash 
 he was then Professor of Classics.  And I did learn an awful lot more Latin and Greek.  One of the three girls who had been with me at The Mount, we\rquote 
d worked all the way through, were very good friends, actually came and stayed with me, so we had a great time together, and we both did lots of Latin and G
reek, and she went on, then, to do it at , I think, Glasgow, was it?  So that was a wonderful two terms, and I did know a bit more Latin and Greek when I got back to Somerville again!  (LAUGHS)
