\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid12285211 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1852626\charrsid1852626 Ruth:\tab }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1852626\charrsid1852626 Oh, that was wonderful!  After being at a girls\rquote 
 boarding school, and in North of Ireland, just the kind of freedom and friendship and activities in Oxford was great.  I can\rquote t understand why women, nowadays, will look back and talk about what a ter
rible time women had in those days.  I mean, really, considering that there were one in seven women to the men, and considering that, at Somerville, it was just assumed that all their students were going to be the best academically, and in all the Societi
es they were going to take the leading roles, they were all going to go on to great careers - I can\rquote t understand why there\rquote 
s this idea that women had a bad time.  I think in science and medicine it was much much harder for them, but in Classics, well, actually, as it happened, I think two out of the three best firsts in my year, were people from Somerville!  You just took t}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid12285211 hat kind of thing for granted.  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1852626\charrsid1852626 
But I found the work, very very hard at first.  I mean, all these men who had been learning how to make G
reek verses since they were about seven, at their prep schools, and they knew everything, but I actually found that by working very very hard, and by the end, I could do just as well as them, if not better, which was very satisfying!  I mean, not that I f
elt particularly competitive, but I just wanted to be good at the subject.  I didn\rquote t like doing Latin and Greek }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid15343836\charrsid1852626 prose that}{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1852626\charrsid1852626  was really hard work, except that it was fun and interesting.  But I loved reading all that literature.  You spent }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid15343836 the first half, roughly, doing \lquote Mods\rquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1852626\charrsid1852626 
, which was basically the language and literature, and you read just screeds of Virgil and Homer and Aeschylus, and Cicero, and Euripides and Sophocles and Plato and Aristotle. How anyone could think of that as work in a nasty sense? And 
I really did work hard.  Of course, the vacations, then, were times when you worked a 40-hour week \endash  you couldn\rquote t have got through it otherwise.  I was lucky enough, I didn\rquote 
t have to earn money in between or anything.  I, in one way, felt a slight outsider, coming from North of Ireland, and there was a bit of a feeling that there was this Inner London clique who all knew each other, and had been to St. Paul\rquote 
s School, and had been tutored by wonderful people to get in, but even they were quite friendly.  And I loved getting into all the societies.  I used to go to the Society of Friends, and enjoyed that \endash  didn\rquote 
t want to become a Quaker, but very much enjoyed going there.  I was involved in the Classics Society, but most of all, I was involved in the Labour C
lub, and really, all my time there from fairly early on became one of the officers - was then the Chairman for a while - and it was such fun and so interesting having these various politicians coming down from London and speaking. All very organised - the
y used to come and speak at Campion Hall - I don\rquote t quite know why Campion Hall \endash  a Jesuit place!  And then there was a particular London train that they always got back to, and they would co}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid5392014 me and dine first.  When I say \lquote Campion Hall\rquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1852626\charrsid1852626 , that was the run of 
the mill people.  But, of course, when Attlee or Bevan came, we probably had it in the Union or somewhere like that.  There were some really good people.  I remember Dick Crossman coming and being a bit objectionable, actually, but quite interesting.  }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1852626\charrsid9514695 And Tony Benn, whom I so agreed with what he said, but really took against him as a person, he somehow seemed so smarmy!}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1852626\charrsid1852626   (LAUGHS)  But Shirley Catlin, as she then was \endash  Shirley Williams \endash  she was one of the people I really remember as being so good, and so st
raight, somehow.  So that was very interesting.  
