l and Ralph, as he then was, Samuel - very definitely Ralph at that time - and they were thought to be the further Left people. In fact, the Labour Club slightly drew up its skirts away from them.  So I think I felt I was very much in parents\rquote 
 tradition in
 that.  I met some really interesting - that was the time, of course, in the Conservative Club, that Michael Heseltine was around, and everyone knew he was going to be Prime Minister!  And Jeremy Isaac and Tony Howard were very much there, and good friend
s, though they felt that I was very unpolitical, and particularly, when I left, I didn\rquote t want to go into politics or journalism, I wanted to use my principles in other things.  But the other thing I was involved with \endash 
 and that was through the Labour Club \endash  was the Movement for Colonial Freedom, which I felt very very much - well, quite passionate about.  And looking back, that, I suppose, ties up not just with the Left-wingness, but with my family\rquote 
