nderful person, partly because she so supported her students, she was totally on their side about everything.  I mean, she would have died, I think, for her students.  For example, I think there was one Somervillian who - now, was she a Jew, or did she wa
n
t to marry a Jew?  But whatever it was, the parents objected and disowned her, so Janet Vaughan threw open her own residence to have the ceremony or the festival part of it afterwards.  I mean, that was just typical!  We all knew that.  But she was also a
 wonderful role model, because she so much continued with her own research. She was so committed to helping people, and helping the impoverished people, and she helped to build up the Blood Bank \endash 
 she was one of the first people into one of the concentratio
n camps after the War. And we knew all that she just expected the highest standards from all her students. Unlike some Principals, she would see each one of us at the beginning and the end of every term, not necessarily for very long, but long enough to h
ave a conversation.  So she was a big influence \endash  not in the content of my academic work, but just in her }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid5983448 standards and her uprightness.  }{\rtlch\fcs1 
