ou discover things yourself, again.  She always objected so much \endash  she was the Ancient History one \endash  if you came along with a narrative that wasn\rquote t what she wanted!  That was the worst thing she could say about what you\rquote 
d done!  And she never gave you the title of an essay, she would just say, \'93Oh Ruth\'94, or \'93Oh, Celia\'94, who was my fellow tutee, \'93Do something on that period\'94, or \'93Have a read of that, and write something\'94
.  So you had to make up your own title and your own question, and that was great.  And it wasn\rquote t really until near the end of the time that she said something like, \'93What you need is a nose for problems.  A nose for problems\'94.  And if she
\rquote d said that to me at the beginning, I think I wouldn\rquote t have understood.  But because she let it emerge out of what ha}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid7086101 
ppened, that really was great.  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1852626\charrsid1852626 My philosophy tutor \endash 
