hat time, was, apart from reading Plato and Aristotle, which was great, was very much a kind of deconstructing things - in one way, very negative, which, in a way I didn\rquote t like, but I found so useful since mixing with sociologists. (LAUGHS) \'93
Does this word}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1852626\charrsid7425029  really}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1852626\charrsid1852626  mean anything?
\'94  (LAUGHS)  I\rquote m really very glad of my philosophy foundation.  (LAUGHS)  I do remember a wonderful tutorial with Mrs. Foot, which, again, I think, summed up a lot for me.  I\rquote d written an essay about something, and I\rquote 
d got confused about this, that, or the other, and then we had the usual discussion, which I always found a little bit frightening \endash  not that she was a frightening person \endash  but philosophy I always - I didn\rquote 
t know quite really how to get at the things, and I talked about something, and then suddenly she put her head in her hands.  Silence.  So I looked out of the window.  And then she looked up again.  And then she said, \'93Good.  Ruth.  Very good.  I don
\rquote t understand now, either\'94.  (LAUGHS)  So, you know, I, again, grasped that the secret of philosophy, at that time, was to \'93not understand\'94!  (LAUGHS)
