Well, one was actually. The main one that I kept in touch with was from Sri Lanka \endash  Desmond Fernando \endash 
 who became a very leading international lawyer in Human Rights, and we did keep quite in touch. Not every year, of course - we were more in touch r
ecently perhaps. But I think he and I influenced each other quite a lot in our outlook on life, both when we were there and later.  When I was at Oxford, I became engaged to a very nice young man called Robin Ditchburn, very much through the Labour Club, 
very much sharing the ideals of Movement for Colonial Freedom. He was then due to do National Service, and did alternative service as a Pacifist, worked in a TB hospital. In fact, our engagement broke up.  He wasn\rquote 
t actually well, and left Oxford early, and then decided to come back to be trained in medicine, which was going to be a long long time, and it just wasn\rquote 
t going to work. So we broke up.  Of course, he and I were very close, and I did keep in touch with him, for quite a while, but then that broke u
p.  But I think we built up, you know, very much some similar ideals between ourselves.  And I think if that hadn\rquote 
t broken up, I might have kept more in touch with that whole circle, that whole sort of Labour Club circle.  I kept in touch a bit, but not on the kind of every week or every month basis.
\par 
