w what research was, or whether I\rquote 
d be able to do it.  Anyway, I felt, very strongly, that I wanted to go out into the real world.  Here I had been supported at Oxford for four years, I wanted to go and be of service somewhere.  And my first thought was de
finitely teaching, but at that time - well, still, I suppose \endash  you couldn\rquote t teach in a State School without doing a further year of Teaching Certificate, or whatever it was called then, and after four years\rquote 
 studying, I did not want to do that.  So the only thing would be to teach in an Independent School, and I thought I would at least try that and see how it was, earn some money, because I needed - I\rquote 
d been given a loan from my school to finance a bit of my university time, that didn\rquote t come out of Scholar
ships, and I think my parents paid a certain amount too, so I knew there was that money to pay back.  So I went off and taught in what, in fact, was a very elite, snobby school \endash  Malvern Girls\rquote  College \endash 
