t really quite explain it, but a whole lot of things kind of came together, and certain myths about it which I then had to disabuse myself of later.  But there was something really quite romantic about the ide}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid551748 a of Africa.  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1852626\charrsid1852626 So I managed to get Scholarships and contacts and so on
, and went back to Oxford to study the Graduate Diploma in Anthropology.  So that\rquote s how all that happened.  And after that, it was almost as if my career mapped itself out, because once you began on anthropology - I mean, if I\rquote 
d been told, when I was sitti
ng in Malvern, in my comfortable room amidst these other very nice teachers, that I would have to go off and do fieldwork all on my own, in a remote village, I would have been a bit scared!  But once you began on anthropology, it was just kind of taken fo
r granted that that\rquote 
s what you would do.  And I suppose also with my Irish background, and that year in Donegal where we used to go barefoot to school, and carry our own water, I felt that, really, perhaps living in so-called primitive surroundings didn\rquote t h
ave too many fears for me, though the Tropics, of course, was a bit of a scary thing to think about.
