\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3820571 ll, it\rquote s what they then called \lquote ethnography\rquote  - I\rquote m not so keen on the word \lquote community\rquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1852626\charrsid1852626  - which was just to cover all those things.  But I think I may have had the idea before I went, that it would be something to do with their folklore.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1852626\charrsid1852626 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1852626\charrsid1852626 
Yes.  I see.  But then you had to do that wider study, for the Colonial Office?
\par 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid3820571 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1852626\charrsid1852626 Ruth:\tab }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1852626\charrsid1852626 
Yes.  For the Colonial Office I had to make sure that I wrote a report which had all that ethnography stuff in, but also had a chapter or a section about the problem of leaving the country to go to the town.  And I did finally write up something.  I didn
\rquote t find out an awful lot about it because it didn\rquote t really seem, to me, to be a huge problem. But I could see it from their point of view and was able to talk a bit about
 it, and put it into the context of how people felt about being. One of the theories of some of the Colonial Office staff was that people were bored, and that\rquote s why they went off to towns, and that didn\rquote t really seem to fit, because people}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3820571  just weren\rquote t bored!  (LAUGHS)  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1852626\charrsid1852626 
So I spent two months in Kamabai, and learnt a certain amount of the language there.  There was actually quite a bit of English around as well, in that time.  A lot of people couldn\rquote t speak any English, but there were some that could, becaus
e it was a local headquarters.  But then I wanted to go to somewhere more remote, and right off the beaten track. So I went to another - first of all I prospected, went further up this main road north, and then off a side road, led by my wonderful driver 
\endash  well, wonderful, but a bit undependable, and a bit of a rascal, but who was very important to me \endash  and then we got out of the car, and we walked up the hillside, off a road, and I still remember that \endash 
 being met just by luck, someone who was a hunter, cla
d in very much traditional garb with his curved knife in his hand, and thinking it was so romantic, walking up this hillside with him and Suri, and we found this small village right up on the very top of a hill, of about 30 huts, really really steep up, a
nd I thought, \'93Well, that is a place I would really like to go\'94.  So that was just a day visit, and we then went back again to Kamabai. But then I decided, \'93That is where I would like to go\'94
, and so with a few fits and starts, and I made a lot of mistakes, but still I finally did settle down there, and the Chief allocated me a small hut just opposite his \endash  a small one-person hut, just opposite his \endash 
 and I stayed there for about five months, or maybe a bit longer, because I moved to a larger headquarters duri
ng the very very rainy season.  I also wanted to study it.  But that was a wonderful place to be, because basically nobody spoke English there. I think only three people had ever been to school, and that was a primary school, sent off from there.  It was 
right off the beaten track.  I mean, you had to walk about two or three miles and scramble across logs across the river \endash  in the wet season \endash 
 to get there. And that was where I really did begin to speak the language, because I had no alternative.  I didn\rquote t 
want to be using an interpreter all the time.  And after a while I realised- my Limba was really bad, and went on being bad, but that it was actually easier to ask questions and get answers in Limba than it would have been in English, because Limba was ju
st the language that was relevant.
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid1852626 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1852626\charrsid1852626 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1852626\charrsid1852626 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1852626\charrsid1852626 
Was your driver also your interpreter, then?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1852626\charrsid1852626 Ruth:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1852626\charrsid1852626 
At the beginning he was.  As I say, he was a bit of a rascal.  When the Colonial Office contact advertised, or sent out a call for a Limba driver, he applied.  Actually - well, what\rquote s Limba, what isn\rquote 
t?  He was a Temne, which was the next door tribe, but he had grown up \endash  so many of them were bilingual, trilingual, round there \endash  and he could speak Limba perfectly well, so that was what mattered.  So to begin with, h
e was my contact person and interpreter, and he was the one who helped me to transcribe, and so that went on all the way through.  So that was also a way in which I learned.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1852626\charrsid1852626 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1852626\charrsid1852626 
And what about the role of the servant that you employed, was he or she important at all?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1852626\charrsid1852626 Ruth:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1852626\charrsid1852626 
He. Not - well, I mean, essential in getting supplies and cooking and managing the Primus and carrying, or getting someone to carry the water, and sometimes telling stories, but really more was just looking after the secular side of t
he activities!  (LAUGHS)  Not a research assistant in the way that Suri, to some extent, was.  But a lot of the time, I was just sitting in the hut, watching what was going on, wandering round the village talking to people.  So often there was some ritual
 
or ceremony or somebody had died, or some news had come and so on, so I would just join in and discover what was happening.  But there were a whole series of cyclical rituals, particularly to do with initiation, so I was able to watch those going through,
 and a lot of them involved a huge amount of singing and dancing. They were rice farmers, upland rice farmers, very very hard work doing that \endash  clearing the bush, sowing the rice, hoeing it in up this steep hillside \endash  and so often.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1852626\charrsid1852626 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1852626\charrsid1852626 This is not growin
g rice under water?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1852626\charrsid1852626 Ruth:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1852626\charrsid1852626 
No. It was on the slope.  And there was a little bit of swamp farming, mainly done by the women.  But this was very much an upland area.  There are some parts of Limba country which were lower, but this was upland rice farming, a
nd very very hard work.  A few other things were grown, but rice was the staple, and the valued and prestige food. And so many of these phases of the agricultural year were accompanied by or supported, promoted, by music and song and dance, so there was a
lways something interesting to see and the agricultural work was interesting to see too.  So the time went quite quickly in a way.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1852626\charrsid1852626 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1852626\charrsid1852626 
Can I ask you about one or two other people? There\rquote s these administrative officers \endash  Mr. and Mrs. Blake.  Mr. L. Flower, and Lieutenant Commander Eckford.  Does that mean anything to you?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1852626\charrsid1852626 Ruth:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1852626\charrsid1852626 
Yes.  Yes, well, this was during the Colonial time, of course, up to half way through, and it actually continued after they were independent, so there were the District Officers \endash  the DOs \endash 
 and there was the Provincial Commissioner.  Blake was the Provincial Commissioner in Makeni, because the whole of the North was one big province.  Then under him there were the District Officers who were in charge of the Districts below that.  A
nd there was a District Officer as well as the High Provincial Commissioner in Makeni, and I used to go and see him occasionally.  He used to play me Bach \endash 
 then Brandenberg Concertos on his record [player] - which was lovely - on his gramophone.  Then there was also another District Officer at more or less the far end, of this main road north, and another big office there in a place where I did spend 
\endash  Kabala \endash  which was another big centre, and that District Officer, who actually came from the Isle of Man 
- no, no, sorry, that was my second visit. The District Officer there ran that whole District, and when I was in this small remote village \endash 
 Kakarima, I came within his District. I used to go up there for supplies. Once when I went down with probably Dengh
i Fever, I went there with a great big rash, so I could go to the hospital!  And I often used to stay in his house, because his house was almost like the local hotel, when I went up there.  So all those District administrators were very kind to me.  I did
n\rquote t spend too long with any of them, because it was my job not to be too close to them.  But they were really helpful.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1852626\charrsid1852626 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1852626\charrsid1852626 
So what about this American Wesleyan Mission?
\par 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid3830351 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1852626\charrsid1852626 Ruth:\tab }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1852626\charrsid1852626 I didn\rquote t see much of them at all.  They were in Kamabai, the first place I was
 in, and I did go and have a meal with them. I think, if I was doing fieldwork now, I would have been very interested in what they had to say, and their reactions and so on, but the outlook, then \endash  and I bought into it \endash 
 was that you wanted to keep away from the administrators and the missionaries, and members of other tribes, because what you were looking at was the traditional institutions of your tribe, and these are all extraneous things.  I mean, nowadays, we
\rquote d be very critical, and I fairly soon becam
e quite critical of that rather narrow functionalist viewpoint, but that was the viewpoint then, so I had very little to do with them.  They did once give me a lovely lift to another part of Limba country where I hadn\rquote 
t spent so long, and I knew they would always have helped me if I\rquote d needed it, but I really had }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3830351 pretty little to do with them.  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1852626\charrsid1852626 One thing they had done \endash 
 not those particular ones, but that particular Mission - they had translated some of the Gospels into Limba, so I found it quite interesting
 to look at that. The people who did the first translation were from Kamabai and used their dialect, because, actually, Limba had a huge lot of dialects, so that people right up at the North of Limba country could scarcely understand people right down at 
the South, so it raises questions about, \'93What is one language, what is one tribe?\'94  But there are always interesting politics about what orthography or what dialect in that situation \endash  which is very common, after all, in unwritten languages 
\endash  becomes the sort of orthodox one for writing it down?  And because the missionaries in Kamabai happened to do some of the early translati}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid15411519 
ons, that has tended to become \lquote the standard Limba\rquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1852626\charrsid1852626  \endash  not without argument, not totally se
ttled, but that happens to be so - and the orthography, on the whole, that I used in transcribing the stories tended to follow their lines. Though when I went to the second small village, their dialect was fairly different, and I could see enough from my 
small amount of knowledge of philology where the sound shift would come - like h\rquote s were changed into f\rquote s, that sort of difference, and i\rquote s into u\rquote s - quite interesting - and l\rquote s into y\rquote s. So that what I called the
}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid15411519  Limba further North, were the \lquote Yumba\rquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1852626\charrsid1852626 
!
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid1852626 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1852626\charrsid1852626 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1852626\charrsid1852626 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1852626\charrsid1852626 
And you also mentioned Delco, the Sierra Leone Development Company?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1852626\charrsid1852626 Ruth:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1852626\charrsid1852626 Yes!  Because that
\rquote s what I\rquote ve got to come on to tell you!  My brother, my civil engineer brother, was, by a total coincidence, working in Sierra Leone at the same time, surveyin
g a railway for this Delco who exported iron ore, and they had discovered another mine further north, and so he was surveying, through the bush, a railway, which he loved, because he was a great adventurer, and great story-teller too.  He just loved doing
 
that, and he was brilliant at it!  So he was actually there before me. Not that he came and met me at the ship or anything, because he was away up country and in a different part of the north from me.  But we did meet up at Christmas, and I went and spent
 
two or three days at Christmas in his camp, which was lovely.  And then one other time, when I had a week off, I went down to another of his camps, down on the coast. So I only met up with him, I think, twice, but I think my parents were very happy to kno
w that he was there!
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1852626\charrsid1852626 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1852626\charrsid1852626 
And then also you mention some Limba people \endash  I can\rquote t pronounce these names properly \endash  but there\rquote s Alimanis Pompoli II, I think that\rquote s a Chief? And then Gbawum II, and Seku II, are they all Chiefs?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1852626\charrsid1852626 Ruth:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1852626\charrsid1852626 Yes, they were.  Some of
 them, I think, were the historical Chiefs.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1852626\charrsid1852626 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1852626\charrsid1852626 
And what was their role in your work, then?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1852626\charrsid1852626 Ruth:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1852626\charrsid1852626 In my work, or generally?

\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1852626\charrsid1852626 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1852626\charrsid1852626 Well, I\rquote 
d probably like to know generally, yes!  (LAUGHS)
\par 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid11993883 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1852626\charrsid1852626 Ruth:\tab }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1852626\charrsid1852626 Well, you see, that was quite controversial because the 
British had this system, as you may remember, of indirect rule, in the Colonies. So they would like to rule through the local traditional authorities, and in some places that worked, that was very straightforward, because you knew exactly who the emir was
, or who the king was and so on. There might be small battles about succession, but basically there were roles.  But in some societies, and the Limba, arguably, were one, there weren\rquote 
t clear-cut traditional authorities.  There were local people of power, that some people would support, and other people wouldn\rquote 
t support.  But, of course, in the British view, they were the established authorities, so the Limba had Chiefs, and these Chiefs were given their powers, and their delegated powers by the British Gover
nment, that they were supposedly coming up from below, belonging to the Limba.  Well of course, these Chiefs were hereditary, so they were able to trace their lines back, and it was all written down in the District Archives that the local Chief I was unde
r, his father was so and so, and his uncle was so and so, and he came down in this way, and the picture was that, in the middle of the 19}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\super\langnp2057\insrsid1852626\charrsid1852626 th}
{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1852626\charrsid1852626  century, there were Chiefs just like that.  In fact, if you look back, some of these Chiefs were really created, the 
concept, really, was created by the British.  They were just people who argued among themselves, and some had wider powers, and some had lesser powers, but they built these up then in a much more formalised way through the British Government. Of course, n
ow, that would be a very obvious way of looking at it, but I think, at the time, there was much more an acceptance th}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid11993883 at these were the authorities.  }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1852626\charrsid1852626 There wasn\rquote t a Chief in Kamabai \endash  the first town I went to \endash  because the idea was that the Chiefship, the pe
rson who was Chief, would alternate between Kamabai and another town not very far away, called Bumban, and at that time the Chief was actually at Bumban, so I was technically under him.  I think I only actually met him once, and was basically around Kamab
ai.  When I went up to Kakarima, the small town, it had its small little Chief in charge of it, though he was under some of the other bigger Chiefs \endash  at least, that was the theory \endash 
 but he was fairly remote from the others, so he had all the kind of trappin
gs of Chiefship, but liked to think of himself as very much the leading authority. I had to be very mindful of his Chiefly status.  He was a bit of a tyrant in his way, but he was quite good to me at the same time.  He rightly, as I gradually came to real
i
se - I mean, (a) he was a bit taken aback when he found that I wanted to go and live in his village, but (b), why not take advantage of this person here?  So he liked me to go along when he went to a big ceremony somewhere else.  He was quite glad for me 
to go along to show that here was this person who was part of his retinue, as it were, and giving him extra dignity and glory.
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid1852626 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1852626\charrsid1852626 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1852626\charrsid1852626 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1852626\charrsid1852626 
Interesting!  And you do especially thank the invaluable help of Suri Kamara.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1852626\charrsid1852626 Ruth:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1852626\charrsid1852626 That\rquote 
s right, yes.  Yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1852626\charrsid1852626 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1852626\charrsid1852626 I\rquote 
m wondering, I think it would be very nice if you could give some kind of picture of where and when storytelling takes place among the Limba? The context, where did you hear them, and what was it for?
\par 
