\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid71221 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1852626\charrsid1852626 Ruth:\tab }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1852626\charrsid1852626 Oh, sorry!  The storytelling!  Right!  Right!  Well, very roughl
y, I mean, if you just want to talk about kind of subject matter, you could divide them into three groups.   There are a lot of stories about animals, which is often thought to be the typical African form, but they weren\rquote 
t all about animals.  And, of cours
e, the animals, in a way, were people.  There were stories overtly and clearly directly about people and adventures.  And there were stories about God, and the beginnings of things.  To start with, I took some of the stories a bit too seriously. There was
 one wonderful story that I recorded in Kamabai, about why God is so far away from us Limba \endash  in other words, from human beings.  In the old days, God used to be close, but tragically, He\rquote 
s now a long way away.  And I heard stories a bit like that, and read about them from elsewhere.  Because what happened, apparently, was that one day, a deer was being chased by a python, and the deer rushed off to God, saying, \'93
Kanu, Kanu, Kanu, help me\'94 \endash  and Chiefs are meant to help people \endash  and so Kanu said to the person, \'93Just be quiet.  This is what Chiefs do.  Don\rquote t chase the deer\'94.  But the python wouldn\rquote 
t listen, and gobbled up the deer.  And then the story goes on and on, because the python is then pursued by an army of ants, and rushes to God, and God tries to stop the ants, but the ants gobble the python up \endash 
 as, indeed, armies of ants can.  And then the ants were pursued by fire, and the fire by water, and it went on and on like that, and God got so fed up of being pestered by these people who wouldn\rquote t then liste
n to him, that he went up above.  And that\rquote s why, now, God\rquote s a long way away, and why we Limba die. God didn\rquote 
t want us to be like that.  And I thought the person who told it to me was a wonderful storyteller, who was blind, and he said, at the end, \'93And I 
was there peeping, and what I tell you is true!  And if it is not true, may I never see again.  But if it was true, when they carry me to my death bed, may I see clearly\'94.  So I thought, \'93Right!  I\rquote ve found the foundation of myth\'94
.  And this was the way th
ings got written up in those days, because this is the foundation of how the Limba see the world, and how they see God and the Beginning, and it really sets up the whole structure, and I could see that this was the way I was going to be able to write it u
p!  Wow!  You know, that was great!  This was a myth \endash  with a big M!  And, of course, at that time, the functionalist anthropologists loved myths, because myth, as Malinowski had said \endash  he\rquote d said a lot of other better things \endash 
 but Malinowski had said, \'93was the sanction of the social order\'94
, and the functionalists liked to see what maintained the social order.  So to have a myth summarising all this symbolically was just brilliant!  So I was really pleased about that!  But then when I went up to \endash  and I recor
ded it - when I went to Kekarama, the smaller village, remote, therefore I would have thought more traditional, so they would certainly know the myth, and I played it to them, I said, you know, \'93I\rquote m going to play you this\'94, (LAUGHS) and they
\rquote d never heard it before!  And they laughed like anything, they said, \'93What a brilliant storyteller!  Wow!\'94  And so I began to have a different viewpoint on the stories and realised that I shouldn\rquote 
t be so literal-minded or jump to my own lab}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid949842 els, but should listen to them.  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1852626\charrsid1852626 
I began to hear how you had individual voices coming through, how of course, there were a lot of themes and motifs and stock heroes and stock situations, but that each person really told it differently.  And there was another story about why death came,
 which I won\rquote 
t go into, but I recorded or took down, from about three different people, and even though the basic plot was the same, there were lots of little variations, but also the whole tone was different.  One, who was rather a tragic young man anyway, who wasn
\rquote t well and couldn\rquote t be initiated, so all his fellows were, and he was a boy, and they were all initiated.  He told us a real tragic one.  But another person told us just a really funny }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid2129879 rollicking story!  And another }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1852626\charrsid1852626 [made] a great point of the character of the snak}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid2129879 e who was in it.  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1852626\charrsid1852626 
So I began to realise how important creativity was, and individual tellers. I was very moved by some of them because, really, the kind of view of a tragedy, of cert
ain relationships, or the humour of others, or the funny little twists of character that were put in just by a kind of wink of the eye, they were so moving and so deep, the storytelling. I did all the proper things that I thought a scholar should do then,
 I transcribed them from the tape at the time, because if you leave it till you get home \endash  it\rquote s about the one bit of advice I got about fieldwork, no methods training in those days \endash  \'93
Transcribe everything, and translate it while you\rquote re in the field, because you\rquote ll forget.  You\rquote ll think you won\rquote t, but you\rquote ll forget\'94
.  So there they were, translated, and all written down, and then in my thesis I put them all down in the text with the Limba on one side and the English on the other side, and some word for word and some freer, and that\rquote 
s the proper way, as a classical scholar, you know!  Learnt how to deal with text!  The real thing were texts!  (LAUGHS)  That\rquote s what reality is, you know, you captured it!  But, of course, when I got back and showed some people my texts, they didn
\rquote t think that they were deep or profound or moving at all, and I was really upset and puzzled by this, until I realised that, of course, the text didn\rquote t capture the reality, the stories - the reality lay in the performance, the audience in
teraction. Because they would say things like, \'93Wow!\'94  \'93\'94What happened then?\'94 and that was part of the story.  And very often they appointed one person to be the replier, to take a particular responsibility in saying, \'93Did he really?\'94
 or, \'93Go on!\'94 \'93Fancy that!\'94  Not with every sentence, they varied quite a bit.  And also there were often \endash  not always \endash 
 often songs in the stories, and the storyteller would sing the first line - typical call and response situation -and the audience would all sing the chorus. 
It was part of taking the action of the story on.  So all this, and all the kinaesthetic and the gestures and the movements, and the atmosphere, and the amazing thing you can do with your voice \endash 
 lengthening, and loud and soft, and dynamic, and stopping, and silences, and exaggerations, and the wonderful idiophones that you have in African languages \'85 a sort of symbolic sound \endash  all }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid71221 that is missing from the text.  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1852626\charrsid1852626 
So I became more and more interested in performance, and that\rquote s, in a way, what was the main contribution in my thesis, or certainly in the book that was written up, and the thing that the scholars, in a way, took out from that.  And it wasn
\rquote t that the Limba were particularly marvellous at performance, I think probably all storytellers potentially have, though they do it in different ways.  It\rquote s just that that\rquote 
s what I happened to notice there, and learn so much from.  So though I could go on and on about the content and the plots and the themes of the stories, and I collected really quite a lot of t
hem, the thing that really I found most exciting, that I learned from the Limba, in a way that has informed all my work ever since, and I realised, actually, looking back, had kind of roots in some of the Ulster wit and talk that there was then.  That
\rquote s really what I got from my fieldwork and what I was lucky enough to be taught by the Limba, by being there.  I couldn\rquote t have got it from books.
