\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid201310 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1852626\charrsid1852626 Ruth:\tab }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1852626\charrsid1852626 Yes.  I mean, I\rquote ve never - well, as a little bit of prolegomena of that, (LAUGHS), I\rquote 
ve always, in a way, been very against the idea that many of my sociology colleagues, for a while had, anyway, that the aim of a good social science researcher is to build theory.  I\rquote 
m most uninterested in that.  I think theoretical insight should help you to understand the world, rather than the world help you to create theories!  And sometimes knowing a
bout the theory can help you to avoid misunderstandings as well, but insofar as the people who inspired me to interpret the world around me, which I suppose is what I\rquote 
m interested in doing, and other people who have stressed the importance not of social st
ructure, like Radcliffe-Brown, or of finding general theories, but people who have pointed me to the idea of human beings as active and thinking, and creating ideas and lives around them, like Weber, rather than - well, Durkheim, now I think, had some gre
at ideas, but at that time, I thought the thing was very much the kind }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid201310 of sociological methods person.  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1852626\charrsid1852626 But I found the symbolic interactionists in America - they were more in America than Britain - just hugely inspiring, and I didn\rquote t discover that work unt
il after my fieldwork, or not consciously, anyway. After I\rquote d done }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1852626\charrsid1852626 Limba Stories and Storytelling}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1852626\charrsid1852626  \endash  I think \endash I discovered Mead and Blumer and Dewey, and then later on, Howard Becker, and I thought they were wonderful. Well, again, the interacting active hum
ans creating symbols in the world around them, yes, and the symbol that the world wasn\rquote 
t just made up of social facts, a la Durkheim, but of symbolic understandings, and again, this kind of social construction of reality idea.  The same with language, that it\rquote s not just something there, but it\rquote 
s something to be used and created, and the sort of processes, not just the products.  So when I kind of suddenly discovered, which I think was probably in the later sixties \endash  I mean, it\rquote s hard, now, to remember exactly \endash 
 discovered collections of books and writings by these people, and the way they analysed social institutions, not as the traditional institutions and the kind of the structure, but as, even in a factory, people creating and negotiating and manipulating
 the rules.  That was a most wonderful new insight to me.
