\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1852626\charrsid1852626 
Well, I mean, the impression given by people who publish stories collected in that way, often is that, somehow, these stories are just happening, and you\rquote re just lucky enough to captur
e them.  But actually, it almost always is a bit more organised than that.  I could tell the people were telling stories, but just about all the ones that I got, I said, \'93Would you tell me?\'94  And that wasn\rquote 
t too remote from what happened, because very often a storytelling session would begin in the evening with, first of all, people telling riddles, and then moving on to tell stories in quite a kind of organised [way] - \'93Now I\rquote 
m going to tell you a story\'94. And people would gather and sing the chorus, so for me to be one of the people saying, \'93Would you tell me a story?\'94 wasn\rquote 
t so totally away from what would happen.  They already had the concept of a set piece but they were set up by me.  This idea of natural recording for stories, well, it could be so, but what\rquote s natural, what isn\rquote 
t?  So quite a lot of them were, I would say to somebody \endash  because I got to know the really good storytellers \endash  \'93Come along this evening, and would you tell me a story?\'94  And I wouldn\rquote 
t always carry my tape-recorder around with me if I went round the village, but sometimes I did, and sometimes people then would sort of say, \'93I\rquote ll tell you a story\'94
, because they knew I was recording stories, and they liked to tell stories.  A few of them I took down from dictation, which isn\rquote t a good way of doing it, but was better than nothing, particularly since the main way where I learnt from were}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13446744  the tape-recordings.  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1852626\charrsid1852626 
Most of them were by men, but not all.  And the best storytellers I think that I knew, were men.  I think the three best, two were
 youngish men that I got to know very well, one particularly, who was the smith, which was a very special secret thing, a smith in Kakarima, the small village. They were both, in different ways, wonderful storytellers, and they were prepared to come along
 and be recorded, or know that if I went along to where they were sitting on the veranda - which was the covered place outside the round huts \endash 
 with a group, with my tape-recorder, they would do it.  The other one was the one in the first village I was in \endash  Kamabai \endash 
 who told me what I thought was the myth about God moving away, and he was a brilliant, wonderful, blind storyteller, and I recorded quite a lot from him.  And then there were one or two one-offs.  There were occasional women that I did.  So it w
as really quite varied.  Some were children and some of them were not very good storytelling, and that was interesting too, but some of them already were.  T}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10631983 
here was no expert role called \lquote storyteller\rquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1852626\charrsid1852626 , unlike with singers and dancers and drummers, where you had experts who\rquote 
d trained themselves.  Some storytellers were accepted as better than others, but basically they were just anybody.
