. Because Limba were ve
ry good at climbing up palm trees and putting a coconut there, or a gourd, and tapping the wine into it.   And the other tribes, apparently, all fell off the trees!  So the Limba used to go and do that.  But they used to camp outside the town and try to k
eep all their money.  So they had a very poor reputation with all the local people as being vagabonds, and then they used to go back with their money.  So they were very much despised.  So I was therefore, in my rather Left-wing committed way, very please
}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10631983 d to be able to write them up!  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1852626\charrsid1852626 
At the same time also, intellectually, very interested that in the official government records \endash  and this is a really generalisable thing \endash  official government r}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid7823240 ecords, they were put down as, \lquote illiterate\rquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1852626\charrsid1852626 , which, of course, mo
st of them were, because }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid7823240 there weren\rquote t many schools, or \lquote high rate of illiteracy\rquote ;  and \lquote economically inactive\rquote .  \lquote 
Economically inactive\rquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1852626\charrsid1852626  meant that they weren\rquote 
t earning money.  But, of course, they were working all the time, producing their palms, and their rice, and feeding themselves, and even selling a certain amount of their palm kernels, and I could see that, \'93
Right, they might be illiterate in Western terms\'94, but they had this wonderful unwritten literature. Again, that\rquote s something which I felt stron
gly about, I suppose, all my career.  Not just about the literature side, but about the way people are labelled in certain ways by particular categories drawn from one set of preconceptions, and one of the obligations, I think, of a good social scientist,
 is to query some of these labels and some of these concepts that we have, whether it\rquote 
s about who can be a musician or who can be economically active, or who can be a researcher, and unpack it by trying to look at what people actually do and think, which ma
y be very different from the perfectly good kind of theoretical intellectual labels that are put on them by people who think that they are the intellectuals in the society. So I felt I learned that from the Limba as well, if you can follow what I\rquote 
m saying.
