 Indian, Fijian, there were New Zealanders, there were people visiting from America, there were Samoans, there were Gilbertese, there were Cook Islanders, there was Tuvaluans, and they were all mixing together on the campus.  So when you\rquote 
re teaching sociology students in Britain, one of the first things you have to try to sort of tell them is that there are other ways of looking at things \endash  the British way isn\rquote 
t the natural way, and there are variations.  Well, those students knew that already.  They were r
eally one jump ahead in that way, although there were still lots of other things you had to and were able to teach them.  And they had wonderful poetry as well as stories and so on. Though I didn\rquote 
t do fieldwork there. I learnt a little bit about it and, of course, it\rquote 
s so wonderful going visiting, at university expense, being flown over that vastly expensive - thousands of miles of the Pacific, it really is huge, to visit so many of these islands. Because we used to go for a week to help people to get start
ed off on the distance learning course, and then keep in touch with }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid726774 them over what they called the \lquote satellite phone\rquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1852626\charrsid1852626  \endash  radio phone \endash  from the capital, from the University.  So that was really so challenging and so exciting.  And the Pacific Islands are lov
