\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1852626\charrsid1852626 Ruth:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1852626\charrsid1852626 
Yes and no.  Bletchley was very much downgraded because,
 of course, the city developers wanted to make their new centre, but originally Bletchley was the main centre, was the big big centre, and so Bletchley has been really not very developed, and the kind of grotty things have been dumped in Bletchley. But I 
very much like the way they planted millions of trees, and, of course, we can just go to the city centre bit when we want to, and we don\rquote 
t have to go other times.  But the millions of trees, and the way you can walk through the whole city on these pathways, without \endash  almost the whole city \endash 
 without crossing any roads, and the great stress they laid on the urban parks and the linear parks along by the rivers and the lakes and so on, it\rquote s really a lovely place to live, in that way.  It wouldn\rquote t be if you didn\rquote 
t have a car, because places are remote from each other, so I wouldn\rquote t like to be without my own transport there.  But for us, it\rquote s been actually really good.  And people weep about the schools, and that is right, that they are not good!  

