Well you asked about Milton Keynes, and I\rquote ll put that together with what I\rquote ve just said about people living there, and about Fiji, oddly enough!  When I was in Fiji, I didn\rquote t do local research, except for the last year, I 
did a little bit on the local urban music \endash  don\rquote 
t quite know what led me into that. Maybe I already had an idea that I might do something on music in England, very faintly.  Fiji was fascinating because there was the Indian tradition and their music, there
 was the European tradition and their music, and there was the Fijian tradition and their music, though the European and Fijian were getting a bit mixed, particularly through the Methodist choirs.  And the local radio station had an English programme, a F
ijian programme, and a Hindi \endash  Indian \endash 
 programme, with music more or less to match.  And I just did a small study of how this music worked as urban music, and all the local groups, and how it was kept separate, and overlapped, and their different names.  S
o I had very much got the idea that you could look at different music traditions and they were all really interesting.  I hadn\rquote t done much on music when I was among the Limba, because I had this idea music is a specialist concern, and only if you
\rquote re properly trained can you study music.
