, and thought, \'93Well!  Huh!  I bet there\rquote s more going o}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid15213109 n than these people make out!\'94  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1852626\charrsid1852626 So I just started on it, and found even a million times more than I had expected, even from my kind of anthropological feeling that if you do an ethnography, you\rquote 
re going to unpack an awful lot more than outsiders realise is going on. People are active, they\rquote ve got their culture, they\rquote ve got their symbolism and so on, so I expected to find a lot, but it was even more.  So that\rquote 
s how it came about.  Of course I had problems doing it, because I was trained as an anthropologist, and my experience was, studying a fairly - well, actually, communities in Africa aren\rquote t that small, but you had the concept that it w
as fairly small, and it wasn\rquote 
t huge huge numbers of people, and you expected to concentrate on a particular kind of village, even though you were extrapolating a little bit more, and here I was, studying a town, a city, of tens of thousands of people!  How
 could I cope with that?  Then, also, though I had very much got explicit in my mind that different traditions were equally valid, I began to realise I had to unpack my own long long held preconceptions about - not the right way, just the natural way in w
hich music was constituted or learned, or performed, or organised, that there was just one set of ideas \endash  audience behaviour, sitting still and listening, that wasn\rquote t natural, that was just one way of doing it, and that was the way I\rquote 
d learned to do it.  So one of the things that was really important for me in doing that study was making it comparative. I got this concept \endash 
 partly borrowed from wonderful Howard Becker, who was a wonderful wonderful inspiring American interactionist scholar, and many other th
ings too - of different musical worlds.  So there was the classical world, there was the jazz world, there was the rock and pop world, there was the brass band world, and certain overlaps, and that to oversimplify, and I also kind of did a critique of tha
t
 within the book, but it was one way of gathering together the differences and the contrasts and the similarities, and highlighting them, and also making the point which, to me, was really important, that each of these worlds was authentic and valid in it
s own right. And the people who upheld it, though \endash  in some views you\rquote d say \'93though\'94 \endash 
 they were amateurs rather than professional specialists, were highly competent active people in their own right, and that their music was an extremely important part of t
heir lives, though part-time, though amateur, it was part of their reality in the world.  
