\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1852626\charrsid1852626 I mean, there was no right way of doing that, and I had to use, in a way I hadn\rquote 
t before, a huge mix of methods.  Participant observation was at the heart of it, and I\rquote 
d like to say a bit more about it, but just go on to say that I also used documentary sources.  I mean, newspapers are a wonderful source which are really very much underestimated, I think, particularly by anthropologists perhaps.  It wasn\rquote 
t just that they gave account of performances, but there are all the little advertisements about, \'93We want an 18 year old to join our reggae group\'94, or \'93The Cock and Bull pub is putting on it\rquote s usual folk performance this evening\'94, or 
\'93We\rquote re auditioning for a part in the opera\'94, and all the little things like that \endash  a huge amount, every week!  And the list of forthcoming music events in various different places.  Or the church advertise
ments, of their choirs and their organs and so on, or advertisements for school teachers and so on. So newspapers are great.  I also, as I hadn\rquote 
t done before, had a research assistant, in a quite different sense from the way Suri Kamara was, who did a number of interviews for me with local bands, pubs, churches, clubs - I think that\rquote 
s the main lot.  I did a postal questionnaire with schools.
