\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1852626\charrsid1852626 Ruth:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1852626\charrsid1852626 Yes.  Yeah.  I mean, I
\rquote ve been so lucky to be at a university that I, well, of course, with all the ifs and buts}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid5265858  and huge objections and so on }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1852626\charrsid1852626 that I so thoroughly approve of, in terms of its mission and what it has done.  I can\rquote t think of anywhere 
where I could have felt that what I was doing was more worthwhile, and to join the University in 1969 and then, with three years in Fiji, but [which] in a way, was a complement and fitted in with the Open University vision, and then to come back and finis
h my career there, and now still to be attached as an Emeritus Professor and a Visiting Research Professor, with still colleagues there, I\rquote 
ve just been so lucky!  And the other thing is that every year was different at the Open University.  At a conventional university you might go on teaching the same course for years, and though, of course, I\rquote 
m sure the good people will change their lectures and re-think everything every year, in practice that would be difficult to do, whereas in the Open University you\rquote re
 always making up new courses with a new group of colleagues, and new challenges, sometimes on interdisciplinary subjects that there haven\rquote t been courses on before. So just from the input personal side, it\rquote s been wonderful.  \tab 
But the other wonderful thing about it is the way, when we first went there \endash  \rquote 69 \endash 
 we knew we were going to a new university that was going to be revolutionary in a whole series of different ways, and that was exciting, and so we were very prepared to be open-minded. I think David maybe had realised it more than me, what I hadn\rquote 
t fully realised, and I think a lot of us coming in hadn\rquote t realised, is that you had to totally change your view of what teaching was. Teaching used to be - you turned up, and you did a good performance in your 
lecture, and I thought I was very good at that.  And then you would have tutorials, and you would draw out students, and encourage them, and you\rquote 
d mark their stuff and that was all great.  But it was all very much centred on you, as the teacher.  What we hadn\rquote t realised was we had to totally change our ideas, and it had to be \endash 
 I know this is really trite terminology now, but it was really different then \endash  students as learners, and what we wanted students to be able to learn and to do from what we offered them.  So we had to think not, \'93What are we clever and good at?
\'94 but, \'93What do the students need to do to accomplish what?\'94  And we wanted them, of course, to be not just people who regurgitated what we told them, which, actually, we came to realise is what often happened in conventional universities 
\endash  people regurgitating your clever clever lectures!  But what material could we give them for them to become critical and thinking graduates at the end of it, not just full of stuff that we sent them.  So we had
 to think really hard about what kind of material, what we would put into it, how we could think of challenging ways to challenge them to do things, and to learn things, and to learn how to do things.  And that was the most wonderful challenge, and it
\rquote s gone on being so because there have been new technologies, and we\rquote ve always wanted to use the best of the recent technologies. But the old technologies - the written word is still \endash 
 well, it was central at the start, and it still is pretty important. For all of my suspicions about over-emphasis on the values of literacy, it is still a great medium.  So to change round your ideas and think, \'93
Well, what do students need to accomplish to be - what do they need to learn, what do they need to be able to do to be a wonderful graduate at the end of it?\'94 was such a different way of looking at things.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1852626\charrsid1852626 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1852626\charrsid1852626 
But why has that change happened at the Open University and not elsewhere?
\par 
