ou mentioned lectures \endash 
 that television would be great, because you could have your lecture, you could do your lecture once, and then it would go out to all these thousands of students, and that would be very effective. Of course, some people are inspiring
 in whatever surroundings, so the film was a place for set piece talking heads, but we came to realise that wasn\rquote t really a very sensible use of television, (a) because - well, somebody wrote a very good book at that time, saying, \'93What\rquote 
s the use of lectures?\'94
  When you came to think of it, actually, often it is just to convey information, which students then write down, without necessarily going through their minds.  I know a bit of that happened in my lectures at Ibadan.  I used to feel really pleased if 
students could repeat back to me what I\rquote d said in the lecture.  But then, when I came to think about it, was that a good use of, say, television time, of lectures?  If it\rquote 
s information conveyance that you want, might the written word be better for that?  All right, there might be charisma and upliftingness and so on, but that\rquote 
s really a pretty small part of it.  So we came to think that television, it was really better to use television to take the students somewhere, to some place or to some idea they couldn\rquote 
t have got otherwise.  Like in science, for example, they had some very good things of people taking them through experiments, that was good, but that you could take them maybe to some international world-famous lab, and show them something going on the
re that they could never have got to otherwise.  Or in social science, one of the television programmes I was involved with was showing them doing some filming in a Nigerian village, or in Ibadan, actually, which they could never have got to themselves, b
ut they could actually see there on film, rather than having me standing there talking about it \endash  which was how we\rquote d first conceived of it.  So television started being really very different from how we\rquote 
d first thought of, because we needed to think, \'93What is an effective use of this medium for the students to be able to do something or learn something they couldn\rquote t h}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid9397276 ave done without that medium?\'94  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1852626\charrsid1852626 
And audio cassettes gradually came in, and they were really good because we could ask the students, even if it 
was a fairly talky piece, to stop the cassette at a certain point, and go away and do something, either on the basis of what had happened there, or some exercise or something, and then come back and switch the cassette on again, and get reactions to what 
t
hey might have done.  So audio cassettes became, actually, very useful as a working way.  We tried to make the written texts like that too, that, all right, there would be some information or uplift or questions or something, but would continually be brok
en up. Sometimes, to begin with, it was more just with self-test questions, \'93Do you know this?\'94 and so on, and going away, perhaps, and looking up something and so on.  But then it also came to be more challenging things like, \'93
What do you think of the idea of this?\'94  Or, \'93What arguments would you use about such and such a thing?\'94  And I think a lot of them did go away and try. Or, \'93What is your personal experience that relates to this?\'94
 and then come back in the written word saying, \'93Well, of course, your reactions are what matter, and there are many different ways.  But here are some possible ways that people might have reacted\'94. Sometimes that overlapped with what they\rquote 
d done, and then they could see the pros and cons of that.  Sometimes it was ideas, \'93Oh yes, we hadn\rquote t thought of that\'94, but they wouldn\rquote t have noticed it if they hadn\rquote 
t tried to work on it themselves first.  So we had to trust them a lot to do things, and they did.
